{"id":"1905.04250","submitter":"Detlev Buchholz","authors":"Detlev Buchholz and Klaus Fredenhagen","title":"From path integrals to dynamical algebras: a macroscopic view of quantum\n  physics","comments":"9 pages, no figures; v2: exposition improved, reference added","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s10701-020-00345-5","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph math-ph math.MP physics.hist-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The essence of the path integral method in quantum physics can be expressed\nin terms of two relations between unitary propagators, describing perturbations\nof the underlying system. They inherit the causal structure of the theory and\nits invariance properties under variations of the action. These relations\ndetermine a dynamical algebra of bounded operators which encodes all properties\nof the corresponding quantum theory. This novel approach is applied to\nnon-relativistic particles, where quantum mechanics emerges from it. The method\nworks also in interacting quantum field theories and sheds new light on the\nfoundations of quantum physics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 10 May 2019 16:36:56 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 25 Mar 2020 20:52:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-05-20"}
