{"id":"1905.04426","submitter":"Darin Ragozzine","authors":"Darin Ragozzine, Matthew J. Holman","title":"Kepler-9: the First Multi-Transiting System and the First Transit Timing\n  Variations","comments":"15 pages, 1 figure, accepted to New Astronomy Reviews for the Special\n  Issue on Kepler Exoplanet Firsts","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP physics.hist-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Kepler-9, discovered by Holman et al. 2010, was the first system with\nmultiple confirmed transiting planets and the first system to clearly show\nlong-anticipated transit timing variations (TTVs). We review the historical\ncircumstances behind the discovery and characterization of these planets and\nthe publication of Holman et al. 2010. It was the first major novel exoplanet\ndiscovery of the Kepler Space Telescope mission. The Kepler pipeline identified\ntwo Saturn-radius candidates (called Kepler Objects of Interest or KOIs):\nKOI-377.01 with a 19-day period and KOI-377.02 with a 39-day period. Even with\nonly 9 transits for KOI-377.01 and 6 of KOI-377.02, the transit times were\ncompletely inconsistent with a linear ephemeris and showed strongly\nanti-correlated variations in transit times. Holman et al. 2010 were able to\nreadily show that these objects were planetary mass, confirming them as bona\nfide planets Kepler-9b and Kepler-9c. As a multi-transiting system exhibiting\nstrong TTVs, the relative planetary properties (e.g., mass ratio, radius ratio)\nwere strongly constrained, opening a new chapter in comparative planetology.\nKOI-377.03, a small planet with a 1.5-day period, was not initially discovered\nby the Kepler pipeline, but was identified during the analysis of the other\nplanets and was later confirmed as Kepler-9d through the BLENDER technique by\nTorres et al. 2011. Holman et al. 2010 included significant dynamical analysis\nto characterize Kepler-9's particular TTVs: planets near resonance show large\namplitude anti-correlated TTVs with a period corresponding to the rotation of\nthe line of conjunctions and an additional \"chopping\" signal due to the\nchanging positions of the planets. We also review the updated properties of\nthis system and propose ideas for future investigations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 11 May 2019 02:42:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-14"}
